<subSubSection id="F1DE44AC8F1DE9B3FB17BC74E5E1821B" pageNumber="720" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="9459F7D31EDFDF83010DBC66D526DBB0" pageNumber="720">
Hitchcock (in 
<emphasis id="0A9ADCD38D7FBE020FBFFEB3F2D5AB02" italics="true" pageNumber="720">Contr. U. S. Natl. Herb.</emphasis>
22: 140. 1920) reconsidered his earlier (1908) type choice, excluding the American plant in favour of a European concept for the species and Wiegand (in 
<emphasis id="924CED9284D25CA4D8B2FBD6766EA506" italics="true" pageNumber="720">Rhodora</emphasis>
23: 55. 1921) concurred with 
<normalizedToken id="1534BEFFF38CB3CF4ADFAB2765EEC6BB" originalValue="Hitchcock’s">Hitchcock's</normalizedToken>
reinterpretation. Baum (in 
<emphasis id="EB0A91B2E96254254EC1F8765CEB7F3C" italics="true" pageNumber="720">Canad. J. Bot.</emphasis>
45: 1846. 1967) also disagreed with the choice of a Kalm collection as type, though on the spurious grounds that 
<normalizedToken id="4CF99DCF046EDFB235282954ED11DCF5" originalValue="Kalm’s">Kalm's</normalizedToken>
name was not explicitly cited in the protologue. However, the Kalm collection is clearly original material for this name, and 
<normalizedToken id="9C5E0AE1A8FF981DEE1E4A173D771BB5" originalValue="Hitchcock’s">Hitchcock's</normalizedToken>
1908 type choice has priority.
</paragraph>
